<FIRST>r a AM-Menorah     12-27 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Menorah,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Group Erects Controversial Menorah in Pittsburgh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Jewish group acting on the strength of a favorable ruling by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> erected a 18-foot menorah outside the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> City-County Building on Tuesday night. `` This adds some light to the darkness of winter nights and is a victory for all the people of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, an attorney for the group Chabad. The city, which contends it has the right to determine what is permitted in front of the building, plans to petition the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday morning to have the Hanukkah symbol taken down. Chabad was permitted to erect the display under protection of a restraining order issued last week by <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. In an involved holiday legal scramble, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> upheld <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCune </PERSON>'s order preventing the city from blocking Chabad's installation of the menorah <PERSON> McCune </PERSON> maintains that the courthouse steps are a public forum open to all types of expression, and <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> ruled the menorah could be allowed until a trial on the matter is held in district court. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last summer that the menorah, a candelabrum associated with Hanukkah, was permitted outside the building because it was accompanied by secular symbols, a Christmas tree and a sign promoting liberty. <PERSON> McCune </PERSON> aided the erection of the menorah Tuesday by reducing a $ 5,000 bond that Chabad would have been required to post to cover some potential court costs incurred by the city. Chabad requested the bond be reduced to $ 1,000 but, in a compromise, <PERSON> McCune </PERSON> set the bond at $ 2,500.
