<HEAD>Singh Government Halts Future Contracts With Swedish Firm Bofors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new government of Prime Minister V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> says it will temporarily stop buying weapons from a Swedish armaments firm accused of paying huge bribes to secure a 1986 contract with the Indian army. The alleged impropriety in <ORGANIZATION> AB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION>' $ 1.4 billion Howitzer gun deal was a key campaign issue for <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, whose centrist coalition ousted <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> from power in last month's elections. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, who is also the country's defense minister, announced in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> will be barred from future contracts until `` they satisfy us in their conduct in regard to -LRB- the -RRB- Howitzer guns.'' At least two newspaper investigations have sought to prove that <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> paid as much as $ 50 million in bribes and commissions to yet unnamed persons. The allegations have not been proved since they surfaced in April 1987, but one newspaper, The Hindu, has published purported documents that it said established <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s links with recipients of the alleged bribes and commissions. The Hindu, and another newspaper, Indian Express, said senior officials in <LOCATION> Gandhi </LOCATION>'s cabinet and persons close to him received the bribes. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> has also been accused of covering up the investigation by handing it over to pliant officers. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> has denied the charges and maintained that his actions have been above board. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> government </ORGANIZATION> said in its election manifesto that it will unearth and disclose the names of the commission recipients within 15 days of taking office. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was sworn in Dec. 2. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> denied that he is not longer keen on probing the <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> deal now that his coalition is power. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said the government order Tuesday covers `` supply of names of recipients and return of money paid in regard to <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> gun transactions.'' `` This shows there is no lack of enthusiasm. We are determined. There is no question of compromise on anything. `` We will do everything to get the names and come to the truth,'' <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said. His colleagues in Parliament loudly thumped desks. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was interrupted by <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members when he continued with the statement. <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Shankar </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayal </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharma </PERSON> adjourned the session amid the uproar triggered by angry shouts from <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s colleagues. Hours after <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s truncated statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said it had been directed by the prime minister to stop all future contracts with <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION>. It was the new government's first major policy decision on the <ORGANIZATION> Bofors </ORGANIZATION> deal since taking office. `` The embargo will be till such time as the company satisfied the government of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> about their previous conduct,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The current Howitzer gun deal apparently remained unaffected by the decision as neither <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> nor the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> referred to i