<SECOND>PM-Panama-Democracy,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Democratic Tradition in Panama Stymies US Efforts, Scholars
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidents since <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> in 1903 have talked about the need to install democracy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Some sent troops under the banner of shoring up democratic rule. But all have been stymied by the lack of democratic tradition in the strategically placed isthmus and by their overriding desire to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rights of passage through the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, scholars say. When President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went on television Wednesday morning to explain why he dispatched troops to remove Panamanian strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from power, he cited the <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> people's desire for democracy and peace `` The people of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> seek only to support them in pursuit of these noble goals,'' he said. `` The rhetoric about favoring democracy is no more than that. It's a pretense,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Peeler </PERSON>, who heads the Center for the Study of the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Bucknell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. The real <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> desire is `` for democratic government, read reliable government, one that wo n't threaten our control of the canal,'' <PERSON> Peeler </PERSON> added. The few times in their 86-year history of independence when Panamanians have supported a truly democratic government, `` We were n't willing to accept their choice,'' <PERSON> Peeler </PERSON> said. That includes <PERSON> Arnulfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, a populist leader elected president twice in the 1940s and again in 1968. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>' left-leaning views did not sit well with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which was not sorry to see him ousted after several days in office by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> commander Gen. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrijos </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Torrijos </PERSON> proved an even bigger problem for the administration, with his pro-Cuban policies and strong nationalism which opposed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> right under the 1903 treaty to use the canal `` in perpetuity.'' Increasing friction with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> led to the ratification of a new treaty in 1978 ceding the canal to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in the year 2000 but reserving the right to intervene if shipping through the waterway were threatened. Threats to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> use of the canal were what prompted the first dispatch of military force to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. When <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, which ruled <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in the 19th Century, refused to approve the 1903 canal treaty with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> sent warships to help the growing Panamanian secessionist movement. But the warships only stood by as the secessionists launched a bloodless revolt and declared independence. In August 1914, the same month World War I broke out, the first ships passed through the canal. But political chaos reigned and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sent troops to register voters and supervise elections. Each time that happened _ in 1908, 1912 and 1916 _ the losing side blamed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interference. By the 1930s, `` there was growing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frustration with the attempts to instill democracy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerome </PERSON>, a professor of history at <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gerome </PERSON> has written extensively about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> efforts to organize the 1912 elections. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s strategic importance grew immensely in World War II, when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence rose sharply to defend oil shipments from <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> against German interception. The hitherto limited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence, which had been centered mostly around the canal, spread to other parts of the country. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in the 1950s and 1960s was ruled by a succession of families from among a thin elite. While not a military state, neither was it truly democratic. <PERSON> Torrijos </PERSON>' rise to power in 1968 transferred power to the military, with a nominal role for civilian governments. Such was the setup under <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, too, after <PERSON> Torrijos </PERSON> died in a 1981 plane crash. `` Various American presidents hoped the roots of democracy might grow,'' said <PERSON> Gerome </PERSON>. `` What they failed to understand is that you ca n't export democracy.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, abhorrent though he is now to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration which nurtured him in the 1970s, enjoyed strong popular appeal among <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s poor. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, who was installed at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military facility as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s president on Thursday based on the results of last May's elections, does not enjoy <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s popular appeal. His main support comes from middle-class merchants. `` Support for him is weak, not passionate,'' and being propped up by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can only be a liability, said <PERSON> Peeler </PERSON>, adding, `` People are n't celebrating democracy, they're looting. Does n't <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> see that?''
</TEXT>
