<HEAD>Riot Charges Overturned in Second Howard Beach Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state appeals court has overturned the misdemeanor riot convictions of three young men in the <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> racial killing and dismissed the indictments against them, saying the trial judge committed two errors. Prosecutors either can appeal, resubmit evidence to a grand jury for new indictments or dismiss the case against the three white defendants. `` We are studying the opinion and we are considering a further appeal, and that's as far as we are going to comment at this particular point,'' <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>, a special assistant attorney general, said Tuesday. The 19-year-old defendants _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bollander </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Farino </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Povinelli </PERSON> _ were charged with taking part in the attack on three black men three years ago in the mainly white <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. One of the victims, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>, was killed when the mob chased him onto a highway where he was struck by a car. The three young men whose convictions were overturned were found guilty in the second trial related to the case. In the first trial, three other white youths were convicted of manslaughter and assault in the fatal attack. Their case is apparently unaffected by the appellate ruling handed down Dec. 11. In overturning the misdemeanor convictions from the second trial, a five-judge panel said the trial judge made two important errors in charging the jury. The panel said the judge, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Demakos </PERSON>, `` over strenuous defense objections,'' furnished the jury with verdict sheets that improperly described some of the alleged crimes. It said the judge also erred by refusing a defense request to instruct the jury on disorderly conduct as a lesser offense of second-degree riot. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Spiros </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsimbinos </PERSON> said he and his clients learned of the ruling Saturday. The Rev. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>, a community activist who advised the attack victims not to cooperate with investigators until a special prosecutor was appointed, said the ruling was `` an outrageous act. It's a smack in the face of all people, especially black people.'' <PERSON> Farino </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bollander </PERSON> and <PERSON> Povinelli </PERSON> were convicted in 1988 of second-degree riot, but acquitted of a more serious felony riot charge for their roles in the Dec. 20, 1986, attack. <PERSON> Demakos </PERSON> sentenced the three on Sept. 19, 1988, to 34 days in jail to be served on weekends over a four-month period. But they were granted a stay pending appeal and spent no time in jail after their conviction. In July, the appellate panel unanimously upheld the conviction and sentences of the three defendants convicted of manslaughter and assault in the first <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> trial.
