<TEXT>
 A Japanese man was arrested at the international airport trying to smuggle nearly 300 endangered turtles and lizards to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in his suitcases, a police officer said today. <PERSON> Tsuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shirawa </PERSON>, 20, was arrested Sunday after authorities discovered that his four suitcases contained 98 turtles and 185 Oriental water lizards, said police Capt. <PERSON> Paiboon </PERSON> <PERSON> Arinchai </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shiwara </PERSON> told police he brought the reptiles from <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and stopped in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> to visit a friend en route to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Convicted of possession of endangered wildlife on Monday, <PERSON> Shiwara </PERSON> received a three-month suspended prison sentence and was fined $ 100. <PERSON> Paiboon </PERSON> said the reptiles were tightly packed into the baggage and bound to prevent them from making noise and moving. Two turtles and one lizard died. <PERSON> Boonlerd </PERSON> <PERSON> Angsirijida </PERSON>, a Forestry Department official charged with wildlife conservation, said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was a major market for wildlife from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Phillipines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries. Last month, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> returned to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> 58 wild animals that had been smuggled into <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Among these were white-handed gibbons, Burmese molurus pythons and slow loris monkeys. <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> has been widely criticized as a major transit nation for illegal international trade in wildlife.
