<HEAD>Gorbachev to Visit Lithuania to Try to Mend Party Rift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will travel to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> in coming days to try to persuade the republic's defiant <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to reaffirm its allegiance to the national party, officials say. When it declared itself independent on Dec. 20 the <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> created the first major crack in the political monopoly forged by <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> attacked the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> party leadership at a meeting of the Soviet party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> held Monday and Tuesday to consider the Lithuanian break with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He accused the Lithuanians of allowing themselves to become `` hostages to separatists.'' But, in a report published Tuesday in the party newspaper Pravda, he also urged `` maximum restraint'' to allow emotions to cool. The 250-member Central Committee unanimously approved the report. The committee decided to send <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and other top party officials to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> `` to explain our position and at the same time to get a better sense of the situation there,'' <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, a Politburo member and the party's chief ideologist, told a news conference afterward. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said some officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting proposed ousting the Lithuanians from the national party or annulling the Lithuanian decision, but others pushed more moderate measures. All were united, however, in their disapproval of the Lithuanian move, <PERSON> Mededev </PERSON> said. `` Most agreed that this was a blow to perestroika,'' he said, referring to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program to restructure the Soviet economy and to a certain extent the political system. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said the trip to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> would take place `` in not very many days'' and that the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will make a firm decision on the dispute in January. The Lithuanian Communist leader, <PERSON> Algirdas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brazauskas </PERSON>, said in an interview that the party officials' visit would be `` good and helpful,'' an editor at Lithuanian Radio said. Despite the postponement of a full decision, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s stand as stated Tuesday refused to recognize the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> party's self-proclaimed independent status. `` No part of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has the right to decide the question about its independent existence with its own program and rules, not taking into account the position of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> as a whole,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in the report approved by the plenum. `` And this means that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> was and remains a part of the united <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> tried for several months to head off the Lithuanian split. At the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> meeting in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Saturday he lashed out at separatists: `` Today, to realize the right to self-determination through secession means to blow up the union, set the people against each other and sow conflict and blood and death.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting the Soviet government should consider the legal status of movements that are `` carrying out separatist activities and whipping up nationalist terror.'' He did not identify any such organizations, but in the context of the debate he likely was referring to <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s people's front, known as <ORGANIZATION> Sajudis </ORGANIZATION>, and other groups pushing for independence from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said the fight against separatist groups would not involve the use of force by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` We're against application of the military or other such methods,'' he said. Thousands of people gathered Tuesday in <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s capital, for a rally in support of the regional party's move, said <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> editor <PERSON> Eduardas </PERSON> <PERSON> Potasinskas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brazauskas </PERSON>, in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Interfax </ORGANIZATION> news service published Tuesday, defended his party's decision as a `` step toward renewal of the party.'' `` The idea is to make sure that the public perceives it as a new political force with a new message,'' he said. <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, however, said the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> party would end up `` crushed by separatist and nationalist forces'' without <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s support Despite <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s bluster, <PERSON> Brazauskas </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> party leaders maintain that the Soviet leader has shown understanding of their move.
