<HEAD>Romanian Princess-Turned-Nun Says Prayers Answered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `He was...' to CORRECT style on Antichrist.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s Princess <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON>, now a nun at an Orthodox monastery in rural western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, said her homeland was saved `` in the nick of time'' by a revolution she never thought she'd live to see. `` I always believed my prayers would be answered,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> said Tuesday. The 80-year-old daughter of King <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> and <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, and great-granddaughter of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s Queen <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> and <PERSON> Czar </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, said her European contacts told her ousted President <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> had to die. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Elena </PERSON>, were executed by a firing squad Monday following conviction by a secret military tribunal. The former Communist leader and his wife had been captured Saturday, a day after a popular uprising forced him from power. He was denounced as the `` Antichrist'' and accused of killing 60,000 people. `` They said 60,000 is enough ... and it -LRB- execution -RRB- had to be done because it would have gone on and on and on,'' <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from the Orthodox Monastery of the Transfiguration near <LOCATION> Ellwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` They had to do it, so they tell me. I personally have no opinion.'' <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON>'s father was king from 1914 until his death in 1927. Her nephew, King <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, was forced to abdicate by the communists in 1947 and lives in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. `` I did n't expect the whole thing, I must say. I've lived with it so long. It's been 42 years since I left,'' she said. `` The strength of the country has always been in its peasantry. That's what <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> was destroying. I hope there is enough of them left and enough intellectuals left to be able to build again.'' Princess <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> was exiled from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> with the rest of the royal family soon after King <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>'s abdication in December 1947. She immigrated with her husband, an archduke of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and their six children to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and then <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> before settling in 1950 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The move ultimately led to divorce. She ended a second marriage to become a postulant, or a candidate for the religious order, in 1961. Six years later, she took her monastic vows and put up a trailer outside <LOCATION> Ellwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to began building an English-speaking monastery for Orthodox women of all ethnic backgrounds. <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> said she has spent much of the past week on the telephone with friends and relatives in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, keeping abreast of developments and consoling friends of the many who died in the uprising. She said that even with the changes elsewhere in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> she did not expect such quick, drastic moves in her homeland. `` Quite honestly, I was feeling very depressed about it,'' she said. `` I thought everybody was doing something but nothing was moving in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> at all. And suddenly, it blew up.'' <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> said she is working with the Romanian <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, to organize a Save <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> Fund. She also plans a special service at the monastery this week for <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s dead. She said she would consider returning to <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> `` if I could be of use.''
