<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heating oil futures jumped higher again today in early trading, continuing the trend that accelerated after a weekend explosion at the nation's second-largest petrochemical plant. Heating oil futures prices had surged Tuesday in the wake of the blast at the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> refinery at <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. The accident at the plant, which normally produces about 4.4 million gallons of heating oil daily, aggravated a price spike caused by the record-setting cold snap that has hit much of the nation and raised the prospect of further spot oil shortages. The explosion Christmas Eve killed two people and shattered windows in buildings as far as six miles away. The second body was recovered Tuesday. An investigation has yet to determine the cause of the blast. Supplies of home heating oil already were tight before the explosion and the accelerated demand has pushed retail prices as high as $ 1 a gallon in some areas. Wholesale prices also have surged, as reflected by the futures market. Heating oil for January delivery, up 10.74 cents on Tuesday, jumped another 4.02 cents to 96.50 cents a gallon in early trading today on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Crude oil and gasoline futures also rose, adding to gains made Tuesday in thin trading. Markets were closed Monday for Christmas. The February contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, was up 5 cents at $ 21.96 a barrel in early trading, following Tuesday's 62-cent rise. Unleaded regular gasoline for January, up 5.49 cents on Tuesday, rose 0.06 cent to 61 cents a gallon in early trading today. `` There's no stopping prices for the short te