 Dec. 26 <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> invasion: By surrendering to <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> diplomats on Christmas Eve, former <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> dictator <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> saved himself, at least temporarily, from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces that ousted him. ... even if <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> evaded the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government again, he still stands deposed and discredited _ and that's an important victory. ... The Holy See may give him to the new civilian government in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, which also wants to put <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on trial. Or it may negotiate <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s departure to a third country like <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. But, frankly, now that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s come to a pathetic end, he's no longer of any real concern. There are far more important tasks facing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. ... Getting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces out of the country as quickly as possible. ... Helping <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s new civilian government build the genuine democracy that has never had a chance to develop in that country. ... Rebuilding <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s badly-damaged economy.
