 Dec. 19 The Cedar Rapids, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, Gazette on <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> pollution: Abuse and indifference finally have caught up with the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. It probably should n't have come as too great a shock recently when the environmental group <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> pronounced `` the father of waters'' a `` soup of toxic chemicals.'' ... <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s contribution to the pollution is varied, although the greatest portion comes from agricultural pesticide runoff. Startling quantities are involved: It has been determined, for example, that 112,000 pounds of the chemical Alachlor flows past a test site in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> each year. The <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> report pointed a finger at specific industries, as well, claiming they are discharging `` metals, solvents, cancer-causing hydrocarbons,'' and assorted other toxins into the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> at <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Muscatine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Riverdale </LOCATION>. ... Any smugness we middle Americans may have felt toward our countrymen in the sooty, grimy reaches of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with their debris-infested beaches is misplaced until we get to work cleaning up after ourselves.
