 Dec. 26 The <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> -LRB- S.D. -RRB- Argus Leader: Under the terms of his new contract, <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> <PERSON> Puckett </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Twins </ORGANIZATION> will make more in a month than President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will make in a year. The star outfielder will make more in a month than -LRB- <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> -RRB- Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> will for his entire four-year term. At $ 9 million for three years, <PERSON> Puckett </PERSON> will average $ 250,000 a month. And he is n't even the highest paid player in major league baseball. Lately, baseball players have been grabbing the spotlight. They have been the beneficiaries of a spectacular, new boom in salaries. The players have shown that they can overpower team owners at the bargaining table, as well as on the field. The new salary structure is almost sickening. It reflects a skewed system of public values that has actually been in place for decades. Do n't blame the modern players for taking what they can get. That's how free enterprise works. If you like, blame the owners, who publicly plead poverty, and then get into multimillion-dollar bidding wars for mediocre pitchers and .225 hitters. Mostly, though, blame those of us who are silly enough to keep going to games, keep watching them on television, keep reading about them and otherwise keep caring.
