<HEAD>Romania Seeking Swiss Help to Recover Any Ceausescu Assets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s provisional governmment will ask <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> for judicial assistance to try to recover any assets <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> may have stashed in Swiss banks before he was ousted and executed. Ambassador <PERSON> Gheorghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolgu </PERSON>, who declared his support for the anti-Ceausescu uprising last week, delivered a diplomatic note to the <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday announcing that a formal request would follow. The new leadership has two months to detail its request. In anticipation of the request, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> on Sunday froze an any assets linked to <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> or his clan, addressing itself in particular to two of its largest banks, <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suisse </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Switzerland </ORGANIZATION>. The action was taken after <PERSON> Moritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Leuenberger </PERSON>, a Social Democratic member of parliament and lawyer, said he received information from unidentified Romanian exile sources that <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> had transferred about $ 400 million, chiefly gold bullion, to <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, much of it in recent weeks and months. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joerg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kistler </PERSON> said a circular from the <ORGANIZATION> Romanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> dated Dec. 25 asked all countries to block any <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> accounts they may be spotted. According to a videotape of his secret trial released by the new leadership in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, <PERS