<HEAD>California Eyes Curb on Sale of `Junk Bonds'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State regulators, spurred by the collapse of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION>, intend to prohibit the sale of high-risk junk bonds from the offices of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s state-chartered thrifts A temporary order will be issued next week by the state Savings and <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, Chief Deputy Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. He said his agency will then begin procedures to make the order permanent. The order will affect about 117 state-chartered S & amp; L offices. Currently, no junk bond sales are taking place in any <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> thrift offices, although such practices have occurred in the past, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. `` Just so no one gets that idea in mind, we are saying you ca n't do it,'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said Tuesday `` We just do n't think it is a good idea.'' An estimated 23,000 investors _ mostly retirees in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ claim they lost nearly $ 250 million when they purchased uninsured corporate bonds sold by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, primarily through the 26 offices of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION>, its wholly owned subsidiary. The Irvine-based thrift was seized in April by federal regulators. The takeover is expected to cost $ 2.5 billion, the nation's largest thrift bailout. Many investors said that because the bonds were sold at savings and loan offices, they assumed they were insured against loss. The bonds, sold in 1987 and 1988, now are considered virtually worthless. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said similar rules on the sale of junk bonds are apparently being drafted by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thrift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION> and by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association for the industry. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thrift </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervision </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday he did n't know of any such orders. The chairman of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, suggested earlier this year that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> consider a ban on junk bond sales from S & amp; L offices. New regulations passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> already require S & amp; Ls to get rid of their own junk-bond investments by 1994; those rules do n't apply to companies that are using <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L offices to sell junk bonds to the public. At <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION>, the actual approval to sell the bonds was given by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporations </ORGANIZATION>, which is under fire for its role. With that approval, the state Savings and <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> gave <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> permission to lease space in each of its offices for employees of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <