<HEAD>Experts: Number of Bugs May Be Down Because of the Cold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cold snap may have had at least one beneficial effect by putting the chill on next summer's bug population. The record cold last week and over the weekend may have killed off large quantities of fleas, ticks, gnats, mosquitoes and flies, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Funderburk </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Bibb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> extension agent. `` It's hard to say what nature is going to do, but the insects that bother man should be less in number early in the summer,'' he said. The bug population could be back by late summer, <PERSON> Funderburk </PERSON> said. And household pests, such as cockroaches, probably wo n't be affected by the cold, he said. The cold also may have slowed the spread of a virus that damages peanuts, tomatoes and peppers, <LOCATION> Sumter </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Extension Agent <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said. The virus is carried by aphids and thrips, insects susceptible to low temperatures, he said. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s peaches may have gotten a boost from the cold. Peach grower <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickey </PERSON> of <PERSON> Musella </PERSON> said the cold was a good down payment on the 850 hours of `` chilling'' temperatures the trees need. `` It could n't be anything but beneficial to us peach growers,'' he said. `` Last winter we did n't get the adequate chilling required and that was one reason our peach crop came up real short.''
