<HEAD>Lebanon Asks Hostages' Release, Complains to U.N. About Israeli Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Lebanon recognizing Panamanian,
Romanian governments, truce in effect. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Wednesday appealed to all kidnappers in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to release their hostages. Eighteen Westerners, including eight Americans, are being held here, most by Shiite Moslem extremists. In other action, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> recognized the new governments in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and announced it was lodging an urgent complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> about new Israeli attacks that killed 12 people and wounded 31. In a separate development, a high-ranking Iranian envoy called a cease-fire late in the day to halt five days of fighting between rival Shiite Moslem militias in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Shortly afterward, police said the fighting dwindled to sporadic sniping. `` The big guns gave fallen silent, and that's a good sign. But unless the sniping is quickly halted, the situation could explode again,'' said a police spokesman, who can not be identified under standing rules. Information Minister <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Rizk </PERSON> read the government's plea to hostage-takers after a two-hour Cabinet meeting held under President <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Hrawi </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> at an army base in east <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. `` On the occasion of Christmas and the New Year, the president, the prime minister and the council of ministers appeal jointly to all hostage-holders to release them,'' the official statement said. The plea is likely to have no impact on pro-Iranian factions holding most of the 18 hostages because government authority has been eroded by 14 years of civil war between Moslems and Christians. The hostage held the longest is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle <