<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strike-bound coal company sued the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> for $ 60 million Wednesday, accusing the union and its members of attempted murder, arson and extortion as part of a nationwide racketeering scheme. The lawsuit was filed in federal court in <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beckley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which also announced it will close its nearby <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> mine because of what it called union violence stemming from the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION>'s selective strikes. The UMW has been on strike against <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION> since January, idling 130 miners. The union also is engaged in a bitter strike against the <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. The lawsuit was filed under the Racketeer Influenced, Corrupt Organizations Act. Although the racketeering statute was intended by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> primarily as a tool against organized crime, it been used frequently against unions, including a 1988 lawsuit by the government against the the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the use of the statute against legitimate organizations, despite complaints by the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> that it had become `` a tool of harassment ... against legitimate businesses and labor organizations.'' The New Beckley Mining lawsuit cites alleged violence at more than 20 coal companies in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> since 1983, when the union began its selective strike strategy, in which the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> targeted specific companies for work stoppages. Previous strikes were industrywide. The lawsuit alleges that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION> employees have been the targets of vandalism, death threats, shootings and beatings at work and at home. The violence `` pervades the coal industry, discouraging productivity and inhibiting the economic well-being of individuals living and working in coal-producing communities,'' the lawsuit says. Union spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Duray </PERSON> called the lawsuit `` ridiculous'' and accused the company of engaging in a `` press-release lawsuit'' by hiring a public relations company to notify the news media of the filing. `` It looks to me like these guys are a lot more interested in trying their case in the media than in court,'' <PERSON> Duray </PERSON> said. District 29 President <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Acord </PERSON> said he knew nothing of the lawsuit or the mine closing. At a news conference on the courthouse steps, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beckley </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasell </PERSON> said: `` The decision to shut down and seal <PERSON> New </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckley </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mine </PERSON> was reached because the continued organized violence orchestrated against <PERSON> New </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckley </PERSON> by the <ORGANIZATION> UMWA </ORGANIZATION> has reached an intolerable level of acceptability by any rational standard. `` Marauding pickets continue to cause great hardship upon the company and its families on a daily basis.'' The lawsuit contends that the union has engaged in a pattern of racketeering that includes 34 counts of attempted murder, 23 of arson and 79 of extortion. Under the RICO statute, the company's requested $ 20 million in damages can be tripled if the union and various individuals are found to have violated the act.
