ion into numerous accounts in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials, however, say <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s personal wealth could total as much as $ 300 million. Deposed as dictator by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops on Dec. 20, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> has been charged in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in two drug trafficking indictments. <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said department lawyers are confident they can document that money <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> sent abroad had been earned illegally in the drug trade. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops seized a slew of records in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was ousted. The four European countries are expected to cooperate with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> request, rules of which are spelled out in international treaties. `` We have had a remarkable display of international cooperation,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. `` These letters were not sprung on these countries this morning.'' Once the bank accounts have been frozen _ as <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> expects _ there is still the possibility they will be barren, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. It's conceivable, he said, that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, his family or his bankers moved money out of accounts since the invasion. Freezing assets is the first step to seizing them, said <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON>. `` These things are not easy processes.'' Any disposition of the money, however, would be by international agreements. Preliminary discussions were also under way with others countries where <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> might has stashed money, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. But he is not thought to have assets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimates