<HEAD>Store Owners Told Looting Not Covered by Insurance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of store owners whose shops were sacked by frenzied looting after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion were told Wednesday that `` acts of war'' were not covered by their insurance policies. `` We regret to inform you that the claim you have submitted ... must be rejected because the insurance policy excludes losses suffered as a direct or indirect result of acts of war,'' said one letter Panamanian insurance companies were mailing Wednesday to their clients. Conservative estimates by insurance brokers and store owners put the damage and losses between $ 750 million and $ 1 billion, according to <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON> said Panamanian businessmen will now ask the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for direct assistance to try to recover losses and resume operations. `` This is a bomb worse than the ones of last Wednesday. The insurance companies are saying that in an invaded country there is no insurance coverage,'' insurance broker <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> said in an interview. Businessmen have estimated that more than 90 percent of the shops were looted on <LOCATION> Via </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Espana </LOCATION> and Central Avenue, two commercial streets in downtown <LOCATION> Panana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Thousands of looters raided everything from food, furniture, televisions and appliances. Only bookstores survived. <PERSON> Lazaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Gago </PERSON>, owner of the <PERSON> Gago </PERSON> supermarket chain, said six of his nine establishments had been looted and added his company was `` in ruins.'' Eight of nine of the Arrocha pharmacies also were looted. A car company said it lost $ 4 million to looters. <ORGANIZATION> Avis </ORGANIZATION> and other rental companies still were looking for cars taken from their lots. Television stations ran ads from car distributors offering rewards for information leading to the recovery of new vehicles. Looting damage in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dorado </LOCATION>, a shopping center for upper middle neighborhoods, was estimated at $ 25 million. <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON> said the chamber would ask for direct <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance `` in the form of equipment, technology and interest-ree loans, something like a Marshall Plan for <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' `` It is our responsibility to rebuild the economy,'' <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON> said, `` but we do not have the capacity at this time.'' Both <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> regretted the damage was done mostly by Panamanians. `` We have committed a grievous mistake,'' <PERSON> Maduro </PERSON> added. `` We attacked our own business establishments while the Americans were attacking military targets only.''
