<HEAD>Typhoon Downgraded to Tropical Depression</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Typhoon <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> weakened rapidly Thursday to tropical depression status and no longer posed a threat to this <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory or any other islands in the western <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, weather officials said. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON>'s sustained winds, which had been clocked as high as 135 mph Tuesday, fell to 30 mph by 11 a.m. Thursday, according to the Joint Typhoon Warning Center. In eight hours on Thursday, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> went from typhoon status, with winds of at least 74 mph, to a tropical storm, with winds from 39 to 73 mph, to a tropical depression, with winds less than 39 mph, the center said. At last report, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> was 220 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> and slowly drifting south and unlikely to re-form into a threatening storm, forecasters said.
