<HEAD>Man Found Dead in Plane Stairwell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 17-year-old boy was found dead in the unpressurized rear stairway of an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet that arrived here Wednesday from <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION>, police said. An autopsy was scheduled to determine the cause of death of the Barbadian youth, whose identity was being withheld pending notification of his family, said <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> police spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnebrew </PERSON>. Flight 928 arrived at <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> just before noon from the eastern <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island, and passengers exited normally through the airport rampway, <PERSON> Kinnebrew </PERSON> said. `` Everybody got off the airplane, and when the ground crew opened the back stairwell, they found the body,'' he said. The rear stair of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 stretch is used on smaller runways without terminal ramps and by ground crews, and is not pressurized or heated during flight, <PERSON> Kinnebrew </PERSON> said. The plane cruised at 35,000 feet on the 1,000-mile direct flight, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON>. `` Death could could have been either freezing or suffocation,'' she said. `` At that altitude there is very little oxygen, and it would have been well below zero degrees.'' She said the stowaway may have entered the plane in the <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION> during servicing, but Eastern did not yet know if he had any connection with the airport there.
