<HEAD>Liver Recipient Monitored Closely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors kept a close watch Wednesday on the nation's second living-donor liver transplant recipient, who was recuperating from follow-up surgery to reduce an infection. <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 16 months, remained in critical but stable condition, according to <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION>. `` She's experiencing some bleeding problems,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, explaining that such complications are common in all liver transplant cases. <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> received part of a liver Dec. 8 from her father, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a dry-wall installer from <LOCATION> Millington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who was the nation's first living-donor liver transplant recipient, remained in serious condition Wednesday Her condition was upgraded from critical but stable on Tuesday. <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 29, an elementary school teacher who donated part of her liver to her daughter for the Nov. 27 transplant, was released from the hospital two weeks ago. The Smiths are from <LOCATION> Schertz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> underwent another operation Tuesday to remove a small abscess from her abdomen, Ms. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> suffered from biliary atresia, a usually fatal congenital defect which is the leading reason for liver transplants in children.
