<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Four soldiers and a sailor were buried with full military honors and 21-gun salutes Wednesday, one week after they were killed in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The funerals, held in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, drew scores of military personnel from each branch as well as high-ranking elected officials and clergymen. Altogether, 23 American troops died in the fighting last week. In <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Pvt 2 <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, 20, was buried in the snowy mountains he called home as about 100 mourners looked on, including his foster parents and the woman he had planned to marry next month. `` I believe when he joined the military, he wanted to believe in something. I want to remember him as a soldier, steadfast and unmovable, who died for what he believed in,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, pastor of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Woodlawn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> is the son of <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s guardian, <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> A military honor guard from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Knox </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, saluted <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s casket one by one at a <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> funeral home The guard fired a 21-gun salute, traditionally reserved for special burials, at <LO