<HEAD>Nearly $1 Million in Gold Taken By Gunmen in Jewelry District Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two gunmen robbed a jewelry district wholesaler of nearly $ 1 million in gold Wednesday after handcuffing and tying up its two owners and five employees, police said. The robbers carried pistols and manhandled their captives, but the victims were not harmed. The gunmen, wearing surgical gloves, took the gold from an open safe, put it into a briefcase and made their getaway, the victims said. <PERSON> Khatchik </PERSON> <PERSON> Djigardjian </PERSON>, a co-owner of <ORGANIZATION> Rope </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with his brother <PERSON> Liouduig </PERSON>, described the robbers as a tall, Irish-looking man who was silent and a short, bald man who spoke with an undetermined accent. The loot included at least 103 pounds of fine gold, gold chains, locks and scrap bars, <PERSON> Djigardjian </PERSON> said. An inventory would determine the exact loss, but it was `` close to a million dollars if not more than that,'' <PERSON> Djigardjian </PERSON> said. Gold closed at $ 406 per troy ounce in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> and $ 408.49 in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> on Wednesday. Police believe about 115 pounds of gold were taken, said Detective <PERSON> Manny </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>. The detectives' report said both robbers may have been Middle Eastern. A Russian Armenian who emigrated to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and then came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1974, <PERSON> Djigardjian </PERSON> said he has run a gold business in the building since 1976.
