<SECOND>PM-Walter Mears, ADV 28,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Dec 28 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Noriega: Cloistered Fugitive Picks Own Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Temporarily, at least, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> picked his own prison by taking refuge at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> _ where Secretary of Defense <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> thinks the ousted military boss might be a long-term resident. That's not what the administration wants, but worse things could happen, and have. So long as the deposed military boss of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is a cloistered fugitive, he is isolated, silenced and confined to small compound, living in a spare, single room. Despite <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s sharp demands that the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> turn over <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stake to the right of embassy refuge seems more important than his case, so long as he is out of power and neutralized. American embassies sometimes have been havens for dissenters, notably in Cold War <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and now <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials argue that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> should not be granted asylum because he is a common criminal, not a political fugitive. In his case there is solid evidence of it, but totalitarian governments have no difficulty constructing criminal charges against their dissenters. Chinese dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> and his wife took refuge in the American embassy in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> more than six months ago, after the government crushed the democracy movement and began a purge of its leaders. He's still there, despite repeated protests from the Chinese, who say the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is interfering in their internal affairs. For 15 years, Cardinal <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Mindszenty </PERSON> lived in asylum in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. He had been freed from a Communist prison in the Hungarian uprising of 1956, and took refuge at the embassy after the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> put down that rebellion. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> finally was able to arrange his release to the West in 1971. Embassies are considered to be the territory of the nations they represent, and when they choose to grant haven, even the most dictatorial of regimes have accepted it. Now, as <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said, lawyers and diplomats are trying to figure out what happens next in the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> case. He left open the possibility that it could be nothing. <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said Tuesday that the embassy is surrounded, with no way out for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and no way in for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities. `` It could be that they'll have a long-term resident in their embassy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would hardly seem a welcome guest; church leaders including Monsignor <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebastian </PERSON> <PERSON> Laboa </PERSON>, the papal nuncio in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, had long been critics of the general's regime. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> embassy had been a refuge for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> opponents when they needed one. Unless there is a deal to let <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> go to exile rather than to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trial, the ousted dictator can keep hiding, but he ca n't run. `` At present, if he leaves the embassy under any circumstances, he will in fact be arrested by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces and returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said Tuesday. Embassy refuge does not apply outside an embassy compound, so as soon as <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> stepped outside guarded <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> mission, he could be seized. The way around that would be a diplomatic deal to let him go into exile. It would have to be distant and silent, lest he regain his voice and try to incite his supporters against the new government. For all the demands that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> go on drug trial, the administration had been willing as recently as October to let him go into exile without prosecution if he yielded power. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> has no extradition agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> so if the church decided <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> should be expelled from the diplomatic mission, it would be to the custody of the Panamanian government. The Panamanian constitution forbids the extradition of any citizen. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Endara </PERSON>, the new president installed with <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> protection after <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was ousted, said if his government had custody, he could not deliver the dictator for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug trial. The fledgling <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> government, apparent winner of the May elections <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> annulled, needs to establish itself and display a power to govern independent of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Yielding up <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would be counterproductive. But the <PERSON> Endara </PERSON> government could put him on trial as a killer; there have been <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hints that prosecution in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> might be acceptable. Until and unless the diplomats find a solution, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> presumably stays put, a captive in spare surroundings that mock the luxuries of his days in power, the cash, cocaine and voodoo cults said to have been his lifestyle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>, vice president and columnist for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, has reported on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and national politics for more than 25 years.
