<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 28,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Dec. 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to correct category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Uprisings As Much Economic As Political</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fury of Romanians against their former government is revealed partly by the economic statistics. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, in recent years, has been the economic backwater of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Alone among those nations _ <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> _ the country's gross national product and industrial production declined in 1988. Its GNP last year, in fact, was about where it was in 1980, while almost every other developed nation, communist and non-communist, registered increases. In that time <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> more than doubled its GNP. While <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s neighbors increased exports between 1980 and 1986, its exports stagnated. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s population of 23 million is exceeded only by that of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s imports were lower than any fraternal East Bloc country. Its per capita gross national product of $ 5,500 also remains the lowest in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, less than one-half that of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and it is falling. Whereas East Germans had an automobile-to-population ratio of one to five, in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> the ratio was just a bit more than one in 100. While Romanian meat production averaged 70 kilograms per capita, that of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> was 160. In effect, the old government was leading the nation into economic decline and lower living standards at a time when growth, if perhaps slowly, was the rule in every other European country, possibly excluding tiny <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. The profile of economic deterioration amid growth emerges from research completed in August and published in September by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. It shows a vivid contrast between communist and capitalist nations. The figures also suggest the urgent need of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to renovate and spur its own economy, in which growth rates have steadily deteriorated in recent years. The <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> research shows Soviet GNP falling from average annual growth of 4.8 percent in 1961-65 and 4.9 percent from 1966-70, to 3.1 percent in 1971-75, 2.1 percent in 1976-80 and 1.9 percent in 1981-85. After a 4 percent spurt in 1986, mainly the result of a 10.3 percent surge in agricultural production, the GNP growth rate subsided to 1.3 percent in 1987 and 1.5 percent in 1988. Agricultural production shrank in the latter years. Reviewing the numbers, and contrasting them with those of the capitalist world, it's clear that the economies of the communist countries as a whole were becoming outmatched. In 1988, the annual rate of GNP growth in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and all countries of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> excepted, exceeded that of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the Soviet bloc nations of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Even the economies of the less developed countries, taken as a whole, showed a growth rate of 3.7 percent, or higher than the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the Communists nations of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Among the large communist nations, a swiftly industrializing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> stands out, registering a growth rate of 11.2 percent in 1988, the third time since 1983 in which it has reached double-digit levels. The stark contrast between the communist and non-communist nations that emerges from the data emphasizes the economic origins of the upheavals. In an age of developing communications, that contrast was obvious to all, except perhaps for a few leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance PMs Thursday, Dec. 28.</NOTE>
