 The <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> has elected the first woman diocesan bishop in the worldwide Anglican communion. The Rev. <PERSON> Penelope </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Bansall </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON> is to head the diocese of <LOCATION> Dunedin </LOCATION>. Her election came about a year after the election of the Rev. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> as suffragan, or assistant, to the Episcopal bishop of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is among 28 national provinces of world Anglicanism. In distinction from the American case, <PERSON> Bishop-Elect </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamieson </PERSON>, 47, will head a diocese with jurisdiction over its priests and parishes. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> church has been ordaining women as priests since 1977, and lists 94 women among its 800 clergy. <PERSON> Suffragan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, the first woman elevated to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> church's episcopacy, said of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>'s new bishop that `` being a first is both a joy and a challenge. I wish for her the same joy, support, and fulfillment that I have experienced here from the people of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>.''
