<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Citrus growers were optimistic that trees suffered little lasting harm from a Christmas frost that caused widespread damage to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> fruit and vegetables and could boost prices for those crops. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s third major killer freeze in six years was not believed as disastrous to citrus trees as those in December 1983 and January 1985. But near-total losses were reported in winter vegetables _ much of them destined for Northeastern markets _ in large areas of the state.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heating oil futures prices surged in the wake of a weekend explosion at an <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> refinery in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, boosting prices and raising prospects of further spot oil shortages. The accident at the plant aggravated a price spike caused by the record-setting cold snap that has hit much of the nation. Supplies of home heating oil already were tight before the explosion. Heating oil contracts for January delivery jumped 10.74 cents from Friday to close at 92.48 cents a gallon Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Retailers rang up modest to moderate holiday sales thanks partly to a late pickup in shopping, but analysts said profits were impaired by discounts widely used to attract customers. Bargain hunters had an abundance of choices because stores slashed prices on items ranging from clothing to electronic gadgets. `` I think the consumer had a very, very merry Christmas and I'm not so sure that the retailers did from a profit point of view,'' analyst <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three days before federal bank regulators approved a delay in seizing Lincoln Savings and Loan in May 1988, the private accountant whose audits influenced the decision switched jobs and went to work for the thrift's owner, according to documents and interviews. The two regulators whose votes delayed the seizure for a year say they did not know at the time that the accountant, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atchison </PERSON>, had taken the new job. But in recent statements, former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> and board member <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said their decision concerning the fate of <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION> _ the nation's costliest thrift failure _ might have been different if they had been informed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> named agency veteran <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLucas </PERSON> as its new enforcement chief and unveiled plans for a fraud unit covering the sale of securities by financial institutions. <PERSON> McLucas </PERSON>, 39, succeeds <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, who resigned as enforcement chief in July after heading landmark insider-trading investigations such as cases against speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> and Wall Street firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The enforcement job is considered the second most powerful position at the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said 1990 could be the toughest year in a decade for the auto industry, which already is hurting from declining sales and temporary layoffs <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> said Tuesday in a year-end statement that 1989 sales of 9.8 million cars and 5.1 million trucks mark a return to a `` more normal trend'' after four years of combined industry sales of 15.2 million to 16.3 million vehicles. He said sales estimates for 1990 of 9.5 million cars and 5 million light trucks are based largely on costly incentive programs across the industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business executives, bank officers, attorneys, real estate brokers and even car dealers have been drafted into the war on drugs _ whether they like it or not. Armed with stiff new regulations passed under the Bank Secrecy Act of 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and other federal agencies are forcing businesses and financial institutions to help track the estimated $ 220 million in profits generated daily by illegal drug sales in this country. `` All that cash does no good stored in boxes. They have to turn it around. That necessarily involves legitimate businesses,'' said <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Intriago </PERSON>, who has started a publication that promises to make sense of the regulatory maze.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first stock exchange in Communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> was set up in the northern city of <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION>, the state <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. It said the exchange was founded Tuesday with a total capital of $ 17 million, and that 152 stocks representing more than 50 percent of its capital were owned by 23 Yugoslav banks. The exchange will list Yugoslav and foreign companies.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices closed narrowly mixed Tuesday on Wall Street as rising oil prices triggered concerns about inflation and interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed 2.13 points lower at 2,709.26. The dollar declined against most key foreign currencies. Gold prices fell in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading after rising in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Bond prices tumbled. Orange juice futures prices soared after a weekend freeze in the South, heating oil futures climbed dramatically, coffee and cotton futures rose sharply, precious metals futures fell, livestock and meat futures advanced and grains and soybeans retreated.
</TEXT>
