<HEAD>Existing Home Sales at Quickest Pace in Nearly a Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th gaf pvs to CORRECT sales rate in Midwest to 950,000
from 450,000; PICKS UP 15th graf pvs, `All of...; Also moved on general
news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of existing homes advanced 3.2 percent in November, with a big jump in activity in the South spurring the fastest growth rate in 11 months, a real estate trade group reported Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing single-family homes rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.59 million units last month, the best performance since sales reached a rate of 3.92 million units in December 1988. The 3.2 percent October-to-November sales increase followed a 1.1 percent decline in October. It was the biggest percentage gain since a 4.5 percent rise in August. Analysts credited declining mortgage rates for the upturn in sales activity. But they said that housing sales presented a mixed picture with some areas of the country such as the Northeast hurting because of a rapid surge in prices in the past several years. `` Some large, high-cost markets have experienced some softening this year. However, many smaller, secondary cities are quite strong,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist for the realtors. He said the disparity in sales between high-cost areas and more moderately priced markets should continue in 1990. Sluggish sales in high-cost areas has prompted some fears of a coming housing recession, but <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, president of the realtors group, said the doomsayers would be proven wrong. `` People who are predicting hard times for housing are not considering how much prices rose in high-cost areas over the past few years,'' said <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, who cited the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, where the median price is up 85 percent from five years ago. <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON> predicted that falling mortgage rates would continue to boost home sales in coming months. The national average for fixed-rate mortgages dipped to 9.69 percent last week, down from a high last March of 11.22 percent. The median price for homes sold in November edged up 0.4 percent to $ 93,000. The West pulled ahead of the Northeast in November as the region with the highest priced homes, recording a median resale cost of $ 150,200 last month. The Northeast was second with a median price of $ 145,800, followed by the South at $ 82,400 and the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> at $ 70,900. The median is the point at which half the homes sold for more and half for less. In November, the sales increase was led by a 9.2 percent jump in sales in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, where homes were sold at an annual rate of 1.42 million units in November. Sales were up 3.2 percent in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> to an annual rate of 640,000 units. The <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> posted a 1.7 percent rise to an annual rate of 590,000 units. Sales in the Midwest were down 4 percent to an annual rate of 950,000 units. All of the percentage comparisons were with October sales rates. When compared to sales in November 1988, the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> had a small increase of 1.1 percent while activity in the South was up by 0.7 percent. However, sales in the Northeast are down 13.2 percent when compared to a year ago while sales in the West are off by 5.9 percent compared to November 1988.
