<HEAD>State Investigates Southern Bell Pay Phone Commissions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s attorney general said Wednesday the state is investigating whether <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> underpaid commissions for pay telephone use to governments in several Southeastern states. Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said the delinquent commissions could total in the millions of dollars but determining the exact amount has been hampered by the telephone company's inability to provide records. The commissions were to have been paid over two years starting in August 1986. <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> knew of the problem in February 1987, but did nothing until a report in The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> last month. `` Computer mistakes do happen,'' he said. `` It is troubling, however, that <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> knew about this problem for more than 2 -LCB- years, yet apparently made little effort to reimburse its short-changed government customers.'' <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> contracts with government agencies to put pay phones in buildings and then pays a percentage based on usage. Southern Bell did not immediately return calls seeking comment. Officials previously have denied any wrongdoing and said the mistake was caused by a computer error. <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said the failure to make back-payments promptly could violate the state's grand theft law. <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said he began sending letters Wednesday to federal, state and local agencies advising them not to accept restitution from <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> until his office accounts for the delinquent commissions. `` As soon as we can determine what appears to be owed, we will advise you,'' <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said in one letter. `` You may well be entitled to to a claim exceeding the contract amount plus interest.'' <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> may owe commissions to agencies in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. In a letter last week to <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said key documents regarding the commissions were lost or destroyed and that the company initially said it could not replace them. Now, however, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> is `` reconstructing'' those records, he said. <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> to ensure that <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> does not attempt to pay restitution and that whatever amount the utility believes it owes be placed in an interest-bearing trust account until the investigation ends. The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> reported that <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> had underpaid <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> agencies more than $ 150,000 in commissions. The newspaper quoted a former utility manager as saying the company knew the revenue reports were wrong.
