<HEAD>Great Northern Claims Takeover Would Prevent Needed Expenditures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nekoosa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday in federal court that needed capital investments at its <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> operations could not be made and that anti-competitive practices would result if <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is successful in its $ 3.8 billion takeover attempt. The testimony came in the opening day of a hearing on Great Northern's request for an injunction to block the unfriendly takeover. Great Northern claims antitrust laws would be violated if the two forest products companies merged. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eginton </PERSON> set aside 14 days for the hearing. The chairman of Great Northern, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON>, testified about the Norwalk-based company's plans for $ 2.5 billion in capital investments and acquisitions in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> over the next five years. Laidig, during questioning by the company's attorney, said <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> would be so laden with debt if it were successful in the takeover that it could not possibly carry out the capital plans. The takeover would result in anti-competitive practices in southern pulpwood markets and in the national market for paper used in personal bank checks, Great Northern also asserted. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive officer, <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>, said outside the courtroom that the projected cash flow after a merger of the two companies would be adequate `` even in a financial crisis'' to finance needed capital expenditures. `` It's an old-fashioned combination of two strong industrial companies,'' <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> said, calling Great Northern's claims `` transparent nonsense.'' `` There is no junk debt involved,'' he said. Great Northern has calculated the resulting debt would total $ 4.5 billion. Attorneys for Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> said a merger would increase efficiency. As of Friday, 73.4 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> stockholders tendered their shares under <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 63-a-share offer, <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> said. The takeover battle is also being waged in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where Great Northern is incorporated. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> is challenging anti-takeover provisions in Great Northern's bylaws, as well as <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>'s corporate takeover law, which forces hostile suitors to wait five years before merging with a targeted company.
