<HEAD>Judge Lifts Ban on Pennzoil Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge in <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s suit over <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s alleged clandestine takeover attempt lifted restrictions Wednesday on <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to file countersuits in other courts. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thelton </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> refused to extend an order imposed by another federal judge Dec. 7 that prohibited <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> from suing anywhere on related issues without approval of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> federal court. <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> had denied any intention of suing, said <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s claims to the contrary were based on speculation, and added that the local court had the power to prevent inconsistent rulings even if other suits were filed elsewhere. The decision was a skirmish in <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s battle to force <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> to sell its newly acquired $ 2.1 billion, 8.8 percent share of <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s stock and prohibit it from buying more stock without court approval. San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> also is seeking to validate the anti-takeover measures its directors took around the time of the disclosure of <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s purchases three weeks ago. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said it was using $ 2.1 billion of its $ 2.6 billion net proceeds from a settlement of its suit with <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> as a long-term investment in <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> for tax purposes. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> said it might invest the other $ 500 million in <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> stock but denied any intention of a takeover of the nation's fourth-largest oil company But <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>, citing <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>'s past attempts to acquire oil property, contended the rival firm intended a hostile merger or a forced restructuring. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s suit accuses <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> of violating federal laws requiring advance notice and a 30-day waiting period before major stock purchases by anyone but a passive long-term investor. <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>, saying <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION>'s suit is based on unfounded suspicions, has asked <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> to dismiss the case. A ruling is pending. Wednesday's decision involved an order <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> obtained Dec. 7 from Chief U.S. District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> forbidding suits by <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> without approval from the local court. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> would inevitably sue to challenge the restrictions on takeovers, and argued that restrictions were needed to avoid inconsistent decisions.
