<HEAD>Report That Bids Are Low Causes Hilton Stock Price To Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotels </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock plunged Wednesday on a report that offers for the hotel-casino company are in the $ 90 range instead of the $ 120 some analysts had believed <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> would fetch. <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION>, which was put up for sale last summer after the settlement of a dispute over the estate of founder <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON>, fell $ 6.87 -LCB- to close at $ 82.87 -LCB- a share on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The Wall Street Journal reported that <ORGANIZATION> JMB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a Chicago-based pension fund manager, had offered about $ 90 a share for <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION>, which would bring the total offer to $ 4.3 billion. Hilton general counsel <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebo </PERSON> declined to comment on the report. Another of the bidders for <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> is <ORGANIZATION> Miller-Klutznick-Davis-Gray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, billionaire investor <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' Denver-based real estate vehicle. The Journal reported that <PERSON> Miller-Klutznick </PERSON> was bidding about the market price for the stock, which was about $ 90 before the Journal report Wednesday. Calls to Miller-Klutznick and <ORGANIZATION> JMB </ORGANIZATION> were not returned. <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> stock was trading at $ 63 per share when <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON>, settled the estate dispute in May In August, <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> stock soared to $ 112 a share on reports that the company would consider at least two formal buyout bids. At that time, some analysts were estimating that shareholders were likely to get $ 120 per share if <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> was sold and possibly as much as $ 140. But the collapse of the junk bond market and fears of a recession have made it much harder to complete takeovers recently, and the stock price has gradually fallen as no deal was announced. <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> had its best year ever in 1987, when profits rose 43 percent and earnings were $ 5.59 per share. Earnings fell to $ 2.72 per share last year and have remained relatively flat this year, rising 2 percent in the July-September quarter to $ 28.1 million, or 57 cents a share.
